segments.text: Okay.

This may sound that I'm serving the brass, but the one thing that I determined after becoming general officer was really that the responsibilities of a general officer are set apart and much greater than below.
And the stresses on a general officer because of that are much greater.
They're just a practice in the army that when you turn a problem over to a general officer, that's as far as you go with it.
It's going to come back solved, or it's going to be solved on the spot.
The positions that general officers are assigned to, generally speaking, are positions of tremendous responsibility.
Sure.
Oh, I don't know.
I guess another evidence that that's true is Fran said, I changed.
What did she say?
In what way?
In personality, in some ways, as a general officer.
I was never conscious of it.
What did she say?
Well, she just said she never was that specific, but she just said, I changed.
More domineering or...?
Perhaps less tolerant, not so much more domineering.
Did you think that you had changed?
Less tolerant, less time for this or that.
No, I wasn't aware of it.
I think what was happening, I was adapting to the responsibilities I had.
And to me, that was it.
I was just adapted.
I must tell you a little story, though, that's one of mine and Fran's favorites.
You know, General Westmoreland's wife, Kitty, was a very attractive woman and a very good partner for him and a very friendly type.
We had just had a ceremony in the Pentagon in which General Westmoreland pinned on the Brigadier General Starrs on two women, our first general officers in the army.
Your first women general officers?
The first women general officers in the Army.
One was Colonel Hoisington, the Director of the Army Women's Corps, and the other was the Chief Army Nurse.
The Chief Army Nurse was a personal friend of Ms. Westmoreland's.
Shortly thereafter, Ms. Westmoreland was in the
beauty shop, having her hair done at Fort Myer when the chief army nurse came in and Ms. Westmoreland greeted her again and congratulated her again on being promoted to brigadier general.
And they conversed a bit and she said, by the way, I'm looking for a husband.
And the chief army nurse was shocked.
She said, what do you mean?
She said, I'm looking for a husband for you.
I want some man to know what it's like to live with a general.
That is a good one.
I thought that was delightful.
That would be a switch wouldn't it?
Speaking of women, let's not discuss the changes at A&M since the 1960s, and women of course is one of those changes.
and I was wondering what you felt.
Was it a good idea to allow women to go to A&M, or a bad idea?
I can rationalize everything that's happened at A&M.
Well, I want your opinions, not a rationalization.
With regard to women, and with regard to voluntary corps duty, cadet corps assignment, but I have differences of opinion.
Now, when I say I can rationalize it,
I recall very much these two decisions, both taken, I believe, by General Rutter.
And I didn't like them.
But I, at the same time, said, well, gosh, I have been in A&M for years.
I have no close knowledge of what the situation is.
How can I be critical of that decision?
But I lament the fact

that we've come to the point, whatever the reason, that we changed the character of that magnificent cadet corps, which I think contributed so much to the individuals in it, and something distinctive in the form of the product of the corps, not just the military services, but to the professions or the undertakings that they entered upon when they graduated.
And I lamented the fact that we found it necessary to admit women to A&M for reason of tradition and for the same reason, the cadet corps.
So I guess you can say that I was so completely sold on the value of that cadet corps that I didn't want to see anything disturbing.
I couldn't understand why we needed to admit women to A&M
when we have, what is it, 13 other state universities that will admit women.
I didn't understand why we had to make the cadet corps voluntary when they had all these other choices for a state institution that can give them the same courses they can get at A&M.
I simply thought, like any old-timer, most of us didn't want to see that change.
What about blacks?
Blacks I have no problem with, whatever.
If you'll recall, the Army is the first institution in this nation that integrated the blacks.
And it was a good move, and it was evident to everyone in the Army that it was a good move.
No, I have absolutely no problem with that.
Those were your ideas then in the early 1960s when all of these changes took place.
Have your ideas changed?
Not a bit.
No, I'm proud of A&M today.
It went from 6,000 to now about 34,000 in 20 years.
I know.
And I'm very proud of the standards they've maintained at A&M.
I'm not close enough acquainted to evaluate that old Aggie spirit, but I can't be the same.
But I'm not sure it's good to be so big, but I understand why we are.
As long as we're a state institution, and particularly one of the two that's permanently endowed,
to be a leading education institution in this state, and the state's paying these bills to keep us in business, how can we say, Mr. Texan, you can't enter A&M?
We're full.
When do you get full?
You don't, as long as you can take care of it.
So I deplore the excessive growth, in my opinion,
But I understand it, and I wouldn't suggest that they change the policy.
I don't know how they could.
What's your opinion of General Orwell Rudder?
I think he was great for A&M.
Even though he brought about these changes?
I didn't know him personally, but I think he was a great leader, and I think he was great for A&M.
Yeah, I disagree with what he did for the reasons I've given.
Sure.
But I wasn't there making those decisions.
Right.
And I...
And I didn't have the facts, and in the absence of those facts, how can I criticize him for making those decisions?
By the way, a highlight of my post-retirement experience was that I was nominated for consideration to be president of A&M to succeed General Rutgers.
No kidding.
I wasn't aware of that.
I was.
I was asked for...
but the university wrote me and asked me to submit information.
And that alone was very flattering, and of course I appreciated it tremendously, and I knew some of the people who had made this suggestion and this nomination.
But at the same time, speaking of General Rudder,
I was not really in close contact with A&M for these years, never have been able to be.
But it was coming through loud and clear to me that the faculty was getting damn tired of the general.
And I think it was mainly over the issue of, what do we call it?
When you've been there a certain number of years, you have tenure.
You know, he always wanted to retain the right to fire anybody.
At least that's the picture I got.
So I never was unrealistic about my expectations in that contest to be named.
Well, what was your response when they asked you?
Oh, by all means I responded, yes.
Do you think you would have liked that, John?
Ten years ago, I would have, very much.
You bet.
Well, what happened?
Did they call you down for an interview?
No, I was never called for an interview, and I think, as I say, my expectations were not very high, but I was flattered just to be considered.
Sure, absolutely.
Anybody would be.
just to be in the pot with the others.
Of course, President Jack Williams was chosen to be president at that time.
Well, I have one more question.
Well, I guess I might have a couple more.
Do you think A&M is a better institution today, or was it in 1940, 41?
Well, you know I can't answer that.
Okay, then one last one.
Not from prejudice, but for lack of real knowledge.
Okay.
What are your feelings toward the draft?
We were mentioning a little bit about that.
Do you think that we should go away from the all-volunteer Army now and go back to the draft, or drafting women too?
What do you feel about these things?
Well, I'd be glad to respond on that.
I feel that we need to go back to the draft, but I recognize how difficult it's going to be, and it's not going to be a matter of just saying, tomorrow we're going to go back.
Yeah.
But with the proper...
national leadership and congressional leadership included, I think we can get back there.
Now, one reason we need to go back to the draft is to get the population involved again, as I've outlined.
But I don't believe we're getting in the volunteer services what we need.
I don't believe we're getting the, we're falling short on numbers, but I don't think that's as significant as falling short
in quality.
By that I mean, really, the capabilities of the people to deal with the technicalities of the services.
So I'd like to see us get back to a selective service system.
Now, when we consider this, we've got to consider how is it going to be made fair this time.
And I have a feeling that we really need to reinstitute some form of universal service in this nation.
And so many people say it's so difficult.
What will you do with all this youth?
Well, by golly.
We've talked before.
I think that one in every
six or seven people in this nation are working for the federal government or the state government or the city or local governments.
Well, why can't we have enough spaces to put these young people in wherever?
In the federal government, the state government, local government, or the military?
And I think if we set it up properly, we'd have it in priorities.
The military needs will be met first.
And thereafter, some other order of priorities.
And there's no reason in the world why we can't absorb those people if we make room for them.
Don't add them on.
Make room for them.
If the Army can take a young soldier for two years and have an effective soldier from him, why can't you have a clerk from high school go into the city hall and be effective for two years?
What about drafting women?
I'm against it, because I don't think women should fight, and I don't think that women are that essential to a nation that's got a vast richness of manhood.
Well, we talked about your early years, your career, your ideas on A&M and a number of other things.
Is there anything that you have jotted down over there that you think that we should have covered?
Anything that I've missed?
Terry, I think you just brought it all out.
There's only one thing that I'd like to say in summary here.
I certainly don't consider that I'm an authority in any of these subjects that we've been talking about, but I do consider that I've been someone committed to...
for 30 years to the security of the nation.
And as such, I've had my own thoughts and considerations and judgments.
So in review, I think that we're going to get straightened out with President Reagan, I think.
But I think we've neglected the importance of national security for several years.
We're out of focus.
balance with our potential enemy.
I think that the world's getting smaller all the time, and as a matter of fact, space is no longer a mystery.
And space is no longer that vast area.
We're in it every day.
So therefore, the families of nations around the world
are just inevitably going to be drawn closer and closer.
Maybe this is a hope for settling some of our problems, because we are going to become more dependent on each other.
Look how dependent, for example, we are today on the Arabian nations, particularly for oil, for our energy.
The strategic materials we talk about in the military, particularly metals, we're more dependent for that
on foreign nations than we are for oil in Arabia.
We can no longer find all the strength we need from within the United States, you know.
So I think that the Russians are pretty much in the same fix in many ways, and so I don't want to give the impression that I'm a doomsday predictor.

things have a real good chance of getting better but we better take care of our homework in our international relations and I don't think that we're really and I don't know what the heck I can do about it but I don't think that we're really equipped to do that and I think you know I see the Pentagon reorganized every time we get a new Secretary of Defense and the Army reorganized every time we get a new Chief of Staff
State Department significantly reorganized.

But while we're worrying about Poland, Afghanistan, and Russia, and what's going to happen to the French socialist government, for example, we're not really, again, we're guilty of not really paying attention to the Western Hemisphere.
And I'm very disturbed about what's happening in Central America.
And of course, I've had a particular interest in Latin America ever since I served in Venezuela and have kept some focus on it.
And we have neglected not only the security aspects of Latin America, but we've taken for granted so long the economic benefits we get there that those become more endangered.
And I would just simply like to see us with a better capability to handle our international responsibilities.
I don't think we handle them.
I'm going to write somebody about that.
I don't know who.
I've met General Haig and know him slightly, but I don't know him well enough to write a dear Al.
Here's my critique.
But I did want to mention that South America, Latin America, is a particular concern to me.

this is something that I you know in my I'm now in isolation here I still think about and then of course we have discussed the something very close to me and that is the the army itself so I guess we've just about hit all the bases well if you think of anything more open we can just add
When you send me that transcript, I'll probably have more things to say.
Thank you very much, General Becker.
